article.headline: Billups scores 36, Szczerbiak 31 in blowout

images.name: Szczerbiak_Wally 020219 inline
images.caption: Minnesota's Wally Szczerbiak, who was 12-for-19 from the field, drives for two of his 31 points.

article.linkText: Minus Garnett, Wolves beat Mavs in Dallas
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves knew they needed a team effort without top scorer and rebounder Kevin Garnett on Tuesday night, especially on the road against the Dallas Mavericks. Chauncey Billups and Wally Szczerbiak stepped up to the challenge. Billups scored 24 of his career-high 36 points in the third quarter, and Szczerbiak added 31 as Minnesota rallied for a 117-100 victory. "I had to keep pressure on the offensive end, and I did that," said Billups, playing his fifth game as the starting point guard since previous starter Terrell Brandon went down with a left leg injury. "The team fed off my energy. Wally started getting hot. Everybody played well. It was a collective effort tonight." The victory moved Minnesota within a half-game of first-place Dallas in the Midwest Division. Garnett was in South Carolina to attend the funeral of his grandfather on Tuesday morning and was unable to get to Dallas for the game. "I told our guys that even without (Garnett), we wanted to share the ball so that we wouldn't be predictable," Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "Offensively, I told our guys to be aggressive, and Chauncey and Wally were aggressive. We were going to find a way to hang in there." Steve Nash scored 24 points, and Adrian Griffin 15 for the Mavericks, who had won eight of their previous 11 meetings with the Timberwolves. Dallas led 56-46 at halftime, but Billups paced a third-quarter charge with 11 consecutive points, including three straight 3-pointers, to trigger a 21-6 spurt that gave Minnesota a 68-62 lead. Billups hit five 3-pointers during his third-quarter outburst, which set a team record for any quarter, as the Timberwolves grabbed a 82-76 lead entering the fourth quarter. "I couldn't be happier for Chauncey because he's gotten a bum rap so far," Szczerbiak said. "He's been on other teams and he's been traded a lot, but people don't give him credit for what he can do. He's come up big for us in big games this year." Szczerbiak took control after Dallas reduced the deficit to 82-81 on Tim Hardaway's 3-pointer. Szczerbiak scored eight of Minnesota's next 11 points, Anthony Peeler hit a 3-pointer, and Felipe Lopez added a three-point play with 5:25 left as the Timberwolves built a 98-86 lead. Rasho Nesterovic had 17 points and 11 rebounds for Minnesota, which also got 10 points each from Joe Smith and Sam Mitchell. Dallas' leading scorer, Dirk Nowitzki, finished with nine points, going 2-for-12 from the field. Michael Finley of the Mavericks missed 16 of 19 field-goal attempts. "We didn't shoot the ball well and our defense lately has been brutal," Nowitzki said. "It was a bad day for us. For them to win without Kevin (Garnett) is a tough loss for us. We knew it would be a tough game for us. They were on fire in the second half."

Game notes
Minnesota is 4-1 since Billups took over at point guard. ... The Mavericks had won 12 of their previous 15 overall. ... Billups' 24-point third quarter was the biggest in any quarter by a Mavericks opponent. ... Billups' previous career high was 32 points. ... Garnett had played in Minnesota's first 52 games this season. ... Mavericks coach Don Nelson was ejected with 2:49 left after collecting his second technical.
